                                <p> By Gareth Jones</p>
                                <p> COPENHAGEN, Sept 23 (Reuters) - South Korean President Kim  Dae-jung told Asian and European Union leaders on Monday that  reclusive North Korea's recent overtures to its neighbours  pointed to the eventual reunification of the Korean peninsula.</p>
                                <p> South Korea and Japan won strong backing from the leaders,  gathered in Copenhagen for a two-day EU-Asia (ASEM) summit, for  their policy of engagement with Pyongyang, which the United  States has branded part of a global "axis of evil".</p>
                                <p> The leaders, representing 25 countries and about a third of  the world's population, also discussed the fight against  terrorism in the wake of last year's September 11 attacks on the  United States and agreed to boost police cooperation.</p>
                                <p> "The two sides (North and South Korea) began to engage in  substantive economic cooperation in tandem with cultural and  other exchanges," Kim said in his opening address to the summit.</p>
                                <p> "These drastic changes point towards a unified Korea."</p>
                                <p> He said the start of work last week to remove mines and open  road and rail links across the heavily militarised inter-Korean  border would "reduce military tension substantially".</p>
                                <p> In a statement, the ASEM leaders "reconfirmed the importance  of engaging (North Korea) in the international community through  constructive dialogue delivering concrete progress".</p>
                                <p> "In this regard, they hoped the prospects for the resumption  of dialogue between the United States and the DPRK (North Korea)  will continue to improve," the statement said.</p>
                                <p> </p>
                                <p> "AXIS OF EVIL"</p>
                                <p> Earlier this year, U.S. President George W. Bush described  North Korea, along with Iraq and Iran, as part of an "axis of  evil", bent on developing weapons of mass destruction.</p>
                                <p> U.S. officials have publicly welcomed recent moves to engage  North Korea, including a landmark visit by Japanese Prime  Minister Junichiro Koizumi to Pyongyang last Tuesday.</p>
                                <p> But Washington remains suspicious of Pyongyang and has so  far maintained a two-year freeze on contacts.</p>
                                <p> By contrast, most countries in the 15-nation EU have  established diplomatic relations with North Korea and, like  Japan, have dangled the prospect of economic aid if the  communist state continues to open up.</p>
                                <p> The ASEM leaders, who included French President Jacques  Chirac, Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji and Malaysian Prime Minister  Mahathir Mohamad, were due to adopt a statement on fighting  terrorism that stressed this was a common threat.</p>
                                <p> "In the light of the tragic events of September 11 the  bridge-building role of ASEM is even more called for," Danish  Prime Minister Anders Fogh Rasumssen, the summit host, said in  his opening remarks to the leaders.</p>
                                <p> "We must firmly reject any attempt by extremist forces to  divide the international community on the basis of race, ethnic  background or religious persuasion," Rasmussen said.</p>
                                <p> </p>
                                <p> POVERTY</p>
                                <p> South Korea's Kim said world leaders must tackle poverty to  remove one of the key problems feeding terrorism.</p>
                                <p> "Poverty brings on desperation and this condition provides  hotbeds for insurgency and fantasies of triumph for the  masterminding terrorists," Kim said.</p>
                                <p> Rasmussen said Europe and Asia could best combat poverty by  opening up their markets to trade and investment.</p>
                                <p> Asian leaders are keen to learn more at the summit about the  euro, launched in January this year, diplomats said. The EU  believes Asians will use the euro increasingly as a reserve  currency, along with the dollar.</p>
                                <p> The leaders are expected to touch on Iraq during Monday's  talks, though differences between them rule out a joint  statement, diplomats say.</p>
                                <p> For example, Malaysia's Mahathir has urged the lifting of  economic sanctions on Baghdad. The veteran leader is a fierce  critic of the Western economic and political model and of U.S.  policy towards the Muslim world.</p>
                                <p> Britain, represented at the summit by Deputy Prime Minister  John Prescott, is working closely with the United States to  secure a tough new U.N. Security Council resolution on Iraq  following Baghdad's decision to re-admit arms inspectors.   (Additional reporting by Natsuko Waki)  </p>
